\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Ps::0>
\f1\fs32 In most generators the magnet that provides the field is an electromagnet, comprised of a steel core wound with coils of wire that form the <term>field windings</term>, as in <xref ref="fig_24_12_png"/>. The <term>field</term> is energized by the <term>excitation   current</term> that flows through these field windings. To maintain the polarity of the field, the excitation must be direct current. <xref ref="fig_24_12_png"/> shows how copper   <term>slip rings</term> mounted on the rotor are used with stationary carbon   <term>brushes</term> to provide the electrical connection from the excitation source to the field windings. The brushes are pressed against the slip rings by springs, and are replaced as they wear.\
